[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] The Example Game Service allows Android and iPhone users to play a game with each other.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] New releases of the backend code are pushed daily.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] New releases of clients are pushed weekly.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] This policy applies both to backend and client releases.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] This policy is not intended to serve as a punishment for missing SLOs.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] Halting change is undesirable; this policy gives teams permission to focus exclusively on reliability when data indicates that reliability is more important than other product features.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] If the service is performing at or above its SLO, then releases (including data changes) will proceed according to the release policy.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] If the service has exceeded its error budget for the preceding four-week window, we will halt all changes and releases other than P01 issues or security fixes until the service is back within its SLO.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] Depending upon the cause of the SLO miss, the team may devote additional resources to working on reliability instead of feature work.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] If a single incident consumes more than 20% of error budget over four weeks, then the team must conduct a postmortem.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] The postmortem must contain at least one P0 action item to address the root cause.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] If a single class of outage consumes more than 20% of error budget over a quarter, the team must have a P0 item on their quarterly planning document2 to address the issues in the following quarter.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] In the event of a disagreement between parties regarding the calculation of the error budget or the specific actions it defines, the issue should be escalated to the CTO to make a decision.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] Error budgets are the tool SRE uses to balance service reliability with the pace of innovation.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] Changes are a major source of instability, representing roughly 70% of our outages, and development work for features competes with development work for stability.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] The error budget forms a control mechanism for diverting attention to stability as needed.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] An error budget is 1 minus the SLO of the service.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] A 99.9% SLO service has a 0.1% error budget.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] If our service receives 1,000,000 requests in four weeks, a 99.9% availability SLO gives us a budget of 1,000 errors over that period.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] 1P0 is the highest priority of bug: all hands on deck; drop everything else until this is fixed.
[src:error-budgets/error-budget-policy] 2At Google, quarterly planning is public, and teams are held accountable to their plans.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In real-world applications, the failure probability of a system usually differs over time; failures occur more frequently in early-life ("burning in"), or as a system ages ("wearing out").
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This is known as the bathtub curve, where the middle region is called the "useful life period".
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The mean time between failures (MTBF, $1/\lambda$ ) is often reported instead of the failure rate, as numbers such as "2,000 hours" are more intuitive than numbers such as "0.0005 per hour".
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] However, this is only valid if the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is actually constant over time, such as within the flat region of the bathtub curve.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In many cases where MTBF is quoted, it refers only to this region; thus it cannot be used to give an accurate calculation of the average lifetime of a system, as it ignores the "burn-in" and "wear-out" regions.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] MTBF appears frequently in engineering design requirements, and governs the frequency of required system maintenance and inspections.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] A similar ratio used in the transport industries, especially in railways and trucking, is "mean distance between failures" (MDBF) - allowing maintenance to be scheduled based on distance travelled, rather than at regular time intervals.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] which would depend on the number of systems under study, and the conditions over the time period.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] To accurately model failures over time, a **cumulative failure distribution**, $F(t)$ must be defined, which can be any cumulative distribution function (CDF) that gradually increases from 0 to 1 .
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] where $\tau$ is a dummy integration variable.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] A concept closely related but different to instantaneous failure rate $f(t)$ is the **hazard rate** (or **hazard function**), $h(t)$ .
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In the many-system case, this is defined as the proportional failure rate of the systems *still functioning* at time t – as opposed to $f(t)$ , which is the expressed as a proportion of the *initial number* of systems.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Thus for a collection of identical systems, only one of hazard rate $h(t)$ , failure probability density $f(t)$ , or cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ need be defined.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] an exponential function with scaling constant $\lambda$ .
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] As seen in the figures above, this represents a gradually decreasing failure probability density.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] which can be seen to gradually approach 1 as $t\to \infty ,$ representing the fact that eventually all systems under study will fail.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In other words, in this particular case *only*, the hazard rate is constant over time.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This illustrates the difference in hazard rate and failure probability density - as the number of systems surviving at time $t>0$ gradually reduces, the total failure rate also reduces, but the hazard rate **remains constant**.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In other words, the probabilities of each individual system failing do not change over time as the systems age - they are "memory-less".
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For many systems, a constant hazard function may not be a realistic approximation; the chance of failure of an individual component may depend on its age.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Therefore, other distributions are often used.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For example, the deterministic distribution increases hazard rate over time (for systems where wear-out is the most important factor), while the Pareto distribution decreases it (for systems where early-life failures are more common).
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The commonly used Weibull distribution combines both of these effects, as do the log-normal and hypertabastic distributions.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] After modelling a given distribution and parameters for $h(t)$ , the failure probability density $f(t)$ and cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ can be predicted using the given equations.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Failure rate data can be obtained in several ways.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] From field failure rate reports, statistical analysis techniques can be used to estimate failure rates.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For accurate failure rates the analyst must have a good understanding of equipment operation, procedures for data collection, the key environmental variables impacting failure rates, how the equipment is used at the system level, and how the failure data will be used by system designers.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Many organizations maintain internal databases of failure information on the devices or systems that they produce, which can be used to calculate failure rates for those devices or systems.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For new devices or systems, the historical data for similar devices or systems can serve as a useful estimate.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Handbooks of failure rate data for various components are available from government and commercial sources.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] that provides failure rate data for many military electronic components.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Several failure rate data sources are available commercially that focus on commercial components, including some non-electronic components.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Time lag is one of the serious drawbacks of all failure rate estimations.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Often by the time the failure rate data are available, the devices under study have become obsolete.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Due to this drawback, failure-rate prediction methods have been developed.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] These methods may be used on newly designed devices to predict the device's failure rates and failure modes.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Two approaches have become well known, Cycle Testing and FMEDA.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The most accurate source of data is to test samples of the actual devices or systems in order to generate failure data.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This is often prohibitively expensive or impractical, so that the previous data sources are often used instead.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Mechanical movement is the predominant failure mechanism causing mechanical and electromechanical devices to wear out.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For many devices, the wear-out failure point is measured by the number of cycles performed before the device fails, and can be discovered by cycle testing.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In cycle testing, a device is cycled as rapidly as practical until it fails.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] When a collection of these devices are tested, the test will run until 10% of the units fail dangerously.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] (FMEDA) is a systematic analysis technique to obtain subsystem / product level failure rates, failure modes and design strength.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Given a component database calibrated with field failure data that is reasonably accurate, the method can predict product level failure rate and failure mode data for a given application.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The predictions have been shown to be more accurate than field warranty return analysis or even typical field failure analysis given that these methods depend on reports that typically do not have sufficient detail information in failure records.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] A decreasing failure rate describes cases where early-life failures are common and corresponds to the situation where $h(t)$ is a decreasing function.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This can describe, for example, the period of infant mortality in humans, or the early failure of transistors due to manufacturing defects.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The hazard rate of aircraft air conditioning systems was found to have an exponentially decreasing distribution.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] In special processes called renewal processes, where the time to recover from failure can be neglected, the likelihood of failure remains constant with respect to time.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For a renewal process with DFR renewal function, inter-renewal times are concave.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Brown conjectured the converse, that DFR is also necessary for the inter-renewal times to be concave, however it has been shown that this conjecture holds neither in the discrete case nor in the continuous case.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] When the failure rate is decreasing the coefficient of variation is ⩾ 1, and when the failure rate is increasing the coefficient of variation is ⩽ 1.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Note that this result only holds when the failure rate is defined for all t ⩾ 0 and that the converse result (coefficient of variation determining nature of failure rate) does not hold.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Failure rates can be expressed using any measure of time, but **hours** is the most common unit in practice.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Other units, such as miles, revolutions, etc., can also be used in place of "time" units.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Failure rates are often expressed in engineering notation as failures per million, or 10−6, especially for individual components, since their failure rates are often very low.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] The **Failures In Time** (**FIT**) rate of a device is the number of failures that can be expected in one billion (109) device-hours of operation (e.g.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This term is used particularly by the semiconductor industry.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] however, this assumes that the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is constant, and that the units are consistent (e.g. failures per million hours), and not expressed as a ratio or as probability densities.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] This is useful to estimate the failure rate of a system when individual components or subsystems have already been tested.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] When adding "redundant" components to eliminate a single point of failure, the quantity of interest is not the sum of individual failure rates but rather the "mission failure" rate, or the "mean time between critical failures" (MTBCF).
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Combining failure or hazard rates that are time-dependent is more complicated.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] For example, mixtures of Decreasing Failure Rate (DFR) variables are also DFR.
[src:error-budgets/failure-rate] Mixtures of exponentially distributed failure rates are hyperexponentially distributed.
